CNN Cuts Its
Losses
------------

Late Friday, after a weeklong trial, CNN settled with
Zachary Young, the Navy veteran spotlighted in a 2021 expos=C3=A9 on bad ac=
tors profiting from aiding Afghans escaping the Taliban. By the time the si=
des began discussing a deal, a Florida jury had already slapped CNN with a =
$5 million bill for defamation, teeing up a further round, in which Young=
=E2=80=99s attorneys gunned for $150 million in punitive damages=E2=80=94a =
number calculated after considering CNN=E2=80=99s $4.9 million in daily rev=
enue and $2 billion-plus =E2=80=9Cnet worth=E2=80=9D (whatever the plaintif=
f=E2=80=99s
economic expert meant by that). Faced with these stakes, CNN cut its losses=
, promising publicly to mine the ordeal for =E2=80=9Cuseful lessons.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

CNN=E2=80=99s loss isn=E2=80=99t a stunner, although many may find it quest=
ionable whether the network=E2=80=99s reporters truly branded Young a crimi=
nal war profiteer, as he alleged. CNN=E2=80=99s real problem was geographic=
al: The trial was set in Panama City, one of Florida=E2=80=99s
deepest-red outposts. Yet what=E2=80=99s truly surprising is how Young=E2=
=80=99s legal team managed to transform this low-key defamation trial into =
a referendum on American journalism. In closing arguments, Vel Freedman, Yo=
ung=E2=80=99s attorney, underlined the presence of reporters in the courtro=
om and watching the stream remotely, then urged jurors to send a message th=
at would ripple across newsrooms everywhere. =E2=80=9CMedia companies are w=
aiting by their phones to see what you do,=E2=80=9D he told them.

=C2=A0

As deliberations began, CNN=E2=80=99s Ballard Spahr team drew Judge William=
 Henry=E2=80=99s attention to the Supreme Court=E2=80=99s 2007 decision ( h=
ttps://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/549/346/?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%2=
7m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F21%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hear=
ing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=
=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) in Philip Morris USA v. Will=
iams, where a $79.5 million punitive damages verdict was overturned as an u=
nconstitutional violation of due process, since
it was based on a jury=E2=80=99s desire to punish the defendant for health =
damages suffered by cigarette smokers who weren=E2=80=99t involved in the c=
ase. Similarly, CNN argued that punitive damages shouldn=E2=80=99t be a veh=
icle for punishing CNN for the sins of the broader media industry, a nuance=
d point that the judge was urged to consider. If the parties had not settle=
d, Judge Henry=E2=80=99s interpretation=E2=80=94that while the jury=E2=80=
=99s punitive damages shouldn=E2=80=99t reflect a general punishment for wh=
at the media had done
historically, the damages could still act as a deterrent against future jou=
rnalistic slipperiness=E2=80=94might have ripened into a potent appellate i=
ssue

=C2=A0

Further complicating matters, Judge Henry was nudged toward the State Farm =
v. Campbell ( https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/538/408/?utm_camp=
aign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F21%2F25%29&utm_content=3D=
What+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_ac=
tion&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) precedent, su=
ggesting punitive damages
shouldn=E2=80=99t dwarf compensatory ones by more than a single-digit multi=
plier. For all the saber-rattling from the right, framing this as a billion=
-dollar showdown, and despite Young=E2=80=99s team salivating at the prospe=
ct of a $150 million punitive windfall, the initial $5 million compensatory=
 verdict actually offered CNN a lifeline, potentially capping its total exp=
osure at $50 million=E2=80=94a bitter pill, no doubt, but far from a ruinou=
s blow.

=C2=A0

I bet the settlement hovered around half that=E2=80=94say, $25 million=E2=
=80=94to sidestep the hazards of an appeal. Some media advocates might balk=
 at the figure, deeming it steep, yet considering the appellate bench is pe=
ppered with appointees from Ron DeSantis and Trump, it=E2=80=99s hardly far=
-fetched. For CNN, it=E2=80=99s a Jake Tapper-sized gulp, the price of shak=
ing off a persistent headache. Late to the game, sure, but as the old adage=
 goes: Better late than never,
especially when the lesson is this costly.

